'''Eric William Wolff''', [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (born 5 June 1957) is a British [[Climatology|climatologist]], [[Glaciology|glaciologist]], and academic. Since 2013, he has been Royal Society Research Professor of Earth Sciences at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name="Who's Who 2015">{{cite web|title=WOLFF, Prof. Eric William|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251168|website=Who's Who 2015|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|accessdate=6 June 2015|date=November 2014}}</ref><ref name="bio - Department of Earth Sciences, Cambridge">{{cite web|title=Eric Wolff |url=http://www.esc.cam.ac.uk/people/academic-staff/professor-eric-wolff |website=Department of Earth Sciences |publisher=[[University of Cambridge]] |accessdate=6 June 2015 |date=14 July 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606160104/http://www.esc.cam.ac.uk/people/academic-staff/professor-eric-wolff |archivedate=6 June 2015 |df= }}</ref>
==Honours== In 2009, he was awarded the Louis Agassiz Medal by the [[European Geosciences Union]]. The medal is awarded 'in recognition of [an individual's] outstanding scientific contribution to the study of the cryosphere on Earth or elsewhere in the solar system'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Louis Agassiz Medal|url=https://www.egu.eu/awards-medals/louis-agassiz/|website=Awards and medals|publisher=European Geosciences Union|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref> In 2010, he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS), the UK's most senior [[learned society]] for science.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fellows|url=https://royalsociety.org/about-us/fellowship/fellows/|website=About us|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref> In 2012, he was awarded the [[Lyell Medal]] by the [[Geological Society of London]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lyell Medal|url=https://www.geolsoc.org.uk/About/History/Award-Winners-Since-1831/Lyell-Medal|website=About Us|publisher=The Geological Society of London|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref>
