Once an important fishing post, the village has recently experienced growth in tourism. The maritime museum has examples of the [[turf roof]] houses once common across Iceland, as well as marine engines and Iceland's oldest rowing boat (1826). According to the 2011 census, Hellissandur and nearby [[Rif, Iceland|Rif]] have 544 inhabitants. Hellissandur is one of the first and oldest fishing villages in Iceland and is traced back to the 16th century. <ref>http://hiticeland.com/towns_and_villages_in_iceland/hellissandur-and-rif</ref>
One of the points of interest near Hellissandur is the [[Snæfellsjökull]] [[glacier]], made famous by [[Jules Verne]] in his ''[[Journey to the Center of the Earth]]''. Just outside the village, there is the northern entrance to the Snæfellsjökull National Park, which surrounds the western and southern sides of the glacier. Nearby is the 412 metre tall [[Longwave radio mast Hellissandur|Gufuskálar]] radio mast, the tallest structure in Western Europe, located 2 kilometres westward.
