[[File:Irma Bencic.jpg|thumb|A bust of Irma Benčić in [[Novigrad, Istria County|Novigrad, Croatia]]]] '''Irma Benčić''' was a Croat partisan and anti-fascist. She was active in the [[Yugoslav Partisans|Istrian resistance movement]] against an occupying [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German army]] during [[World War II]]. Benčić was killed in March 1945 by the Germans; her efforts to liberate Istra are commemorated by a memorial park in her name.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://tvistra.hr/obiljezena-72-obljetnica-stradanja-irme-bencic/|title=Obilježena 72. obljetnica stradanja Irme Benčić - TV Istra|date=2017-03-03|work=TV Istra|access-date=2018-10-06|language=hr-HR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tracesofwar.com/sights/90811/Bust-Irma-Ben%C4%8Di%C4%87.htm|title=Bust Irma Benčić - Novigrad - TracesOfWar.com|website=www.tracesofwar.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> == Biography == Irma Benčić was a native of [[Istria|Istria Province]], part of modern day [[Croatia]]; during Irma's lifetime, the province was part of [[Yugoslavia]]. When [[Nazi Germany]] [[Invasion of Yugoslavia|invaded]] Yugoslavia in 1940, a resistance movement, later widely referred to as the NOP ([[:hr:Istra u Narodnooslobodilačkom pokretu|hr]]), was formed in Istria to oppose the German occupiers of the [[Operational Zone of the Adriatic Littoral]]. Benčić joined the partisans during the conflict, actively resisting against the Germans. She was killed by the German army on the night of 1 March 1945 in [[Novigrad, Istria County|Novigrad]], two months before the city was liberated by the advancing Yugoslav army.<ref name=":0" /><ref>Buršić, Herman, ''Od ropstva do slobode: Istra 1918 - 1945. Male bilješke o velikom putu'', Histria Croatica C.A.S.H., Pula, 2011., {{ISBN|978-953-255-030-6}}, str. 487.</ref>
